data.value:
Google has enforced stricter privacy policies, denying us the All Files Access permission. This permission is essential for several features of our application, and without it, some functionalities are either unavailable or significantly impaired. These features include:
1 - Split View: This feature is no longer available for FTP, SMB, Google Drive, and Azure Blob Storage sessions. Users will not be able to browse the file structure on their local device or easily copy and move files between the device and the remote session. Only the file structure on the remote host will be visible, making file management cumbersome.
2 - RDP Sessions - Client file browsing from remote host: Remote hosts can no longer browse through client files on the Android device, hindering file manipulation between the remote host and the client.
3 - SSH Sessions - zmodem: Zmodem support for uploading and downloading is no longer available.

data.name: GlobalAutoTypeCommandsDescription
data.value:
TAB - Moves focus to the next field. e.g., Pressing TAB moves the cursor from the "Email" field to the "Password" field in a login form.
ENTER - Submits a form or activates a button. e.g., Pressing ENTER submits a search query on a search engine.
INSERT - Inserts a character at the current cursor position. e.g., INSERT could be used in a text editor to toggle between inserting and overwriting text.
DELETE - Deletes a character or item. e.g., Pressing DELETE removes the currently selected file in a file manager.
SPACE - Adds a space character or activates a focused button. e.g., Pressing SPACE adds a space between words in a text field.
ESC - Cancels an action or closes a dialog. e.g., Pressing ESC closes a popup or cancels a file download dialog.
USERNAME - Inserts the username value in the current field.
PASSWORD - Inserts the password value in the current field.

data.name: RekeyOperationDescriptionAndWarning
data.value:
You are about to start an irreversible rekey operation on your Hub. This process generates a new encryption key and re-encrypts sensitive data. Depending on the volume of data, the process could last from a few minutes to several hours. Users will be locked out during this time. Once the process is completed:
  • Application identities will be disabled until regenerated.
  • Services (PAM, encryption, and reporting) and PowerShell scripts will need to use the newly generated credentials.
  • Users will be reinvited automatically, and user states will be updated in the administration view.
Ensure you have a stable Internet connection, disable VPNs, and leave your browser open and your computer on throughout the operation.

data.name: SecurityWeakness_AESForZipEncryption
data.value:
The ZipCrypto algorithm is considered insecure, and AES should be used instead. It is susceptible to known-plaintext attacks, which can allow recovering the content of the archive without knowing the password (see https://blog.devolutions.net/2020/08/why-you-should-never-use-zipcrypto for details on this attack).
In Options â†’ Advanced, uncheck â€œUse ZipCrypto compression (insecure)â€.

data.name: SecurityWeakness_AllowDataSourcePasswordVariable
data.value:
When this option is enabled, the variable DATA_SOURCE_PASSWORD will resolve to the data source password. This option should be disabled if it is not needed.
In Administration Settings â†’ Password Policy, uncheck â€œAllow data source password variable.â€

data.name: SecurityWeakness_AllowOffline
data.value: By default, offline mode is enabled and allows Remote Desktop Manager to automatically cache credentials stored in entries on the client system. This feature should be turned off in high-security environments to avoid unnecessary sensitive data exposure.

data.name: SecurityWeakness_ApplicationPasswordEncryption
data.value:
The application password should be used to encrypt sensitive information in the Remote Desktop Manager configuration files.
In Options â†’ Security â†’ Application Security (local), choose â€œuse application passwordâ€ and check â€œEncrypt local files using the application password.â€

data.name: SecurityWeakness_CustomUserPasswordExpiration
data.value:
Some security standards require passwords to be changed at regular intervals. PCI DSS 4.0 requires passwords to be changed every 90 days when the password is the only authentication factor.
Password expiration can be configured in System Settings â†’ Security Settings â†’ "Custom user password expiration (days)".

data.name: SecurityWeakness_CVEAffected
data.value:
Security updates are available for this version.
The following vulnerabilities have been addressed in newer releases: {0}
Update to the latest version to apply these security fixes.
This product uses the NVD API but is not endorsed or certified by the NVD.

data.name: SecurityWeakness_DefaultPasswordTemplate
data.value:
Password templates set requirements for passwords generated with the password generators.
In File â†’ Templates, select Password Templates to create a template. Then, the default template can be selected in Administration â†’ System Settings â†’ Password Templates.

data.name: SecurityWeakness_EnableHttpsRecommendation
data.value:
HTTPS is used to protect the communication between the client and the server hosting the data source. Traffic over HTTP is unencrypted and is susceptible to being intercepted and tampered with by a malicious third-party.
Configure a TLS certificate on the server and set the data source URL to start with â€œhttps://â€.
See https://kb.devolutions.net/dps_configure_ssl.html

data.name: SecurityWeakness_EnableSQTDERecommendation
data.value: Transparent Data Encryption encrypts the database data at rest, which mitigates risks should physical drives or backup tapes be stolen.

data.name: SecurityWeakness_EnableSSLForSQLServerRecommendation
data.value:
TLS protects communications between Remote Desktop Manager and the SQL Server instance.
Configure SQL Server to support TLS connections and add "encrypt=true" to the SQL Server connection string.

data.name: SecurityWeakness_EnforceMfaRecommendation
data.value:
Multifactor authentication (MFA) requires an additional means of authentication when connecting to a data source. This control prevents abuse of compromised, leaked, or weak passwords. The software can be configured to enforce MFA requirements for all users.
In Administration â†’ System Settings, enable "Force data source multifactor configuration".

data.name: SecurityWeakness_EnforceOriginCheckForAutofill
data.value:
Origin check enforcement for web autofill is not enabled. Enforcing origin checks ensures that credentials are only auto-filled on the intended websites, preventing phishing attacks and credential leakage.
In Options â†’ Types â†’ Web, set "Enforce origin check for autofill" to "Yes".

data.name: SecurityWeakness_IgnoreAppCertificateErrors
data.value:
Validating certificates guarantees that the connection is established with the intended party and protects against data interception attacks.
In Options â†’ Security â†’ Certificate security, uncheck "Ignore application certificate errors."

data.name: SecurityWeakness_InsecureSshAlgorithms
data.value:
Using insecure SSH algorithms can compromise the security of your SSH connections
In File â†’ Settings â†’ Types â†’ Sessions â†’ Terminal â†’ Algorithm support, disable insecure SSH algorithms.

data.name: SecurityWeakness_InsecureSshKey
data.value:
Using insecure SSH keys can pose significant security risks, as they can be more easily compromised, allowing unauthorized access to your systems
Can be deleted from your local files

data.name: SecurityWeakness_LogUserVaultActivities
data.value:
Activity logs on user vaults can provide additional information during incident response.
In Administration â†’ System Settings â†’ User vault, check "Log user vault activities".

data.name: SecurityWeakness_MasterkeyConfigured
data.value:
Using a master key encrypts the sensitive content of XML-based data source files.
The master key can be set under File â†’ Change master key.

data.name: SecurityWeakness_MinimalVersion
data.value: Setting a minimum RDM version is recommended to ensure clients are up to date and have the latest security features.

data.name: SecurityWeakness_MinimalVersionX
data.value: Setting a minimum RDM version is recommended to ensure clients have the latest security features. You do not have a minimum version configured for {0}

data.name: SecurityWeakness_PasswordStrengthAnalyzer
data.value:
Zxcvbn is recommended over the legacy password strength analyzer as it is more reliable.
In Administration â†’ System Settings â†’ Password Policy, set Password strength calculator to "Zxcvbn".

data.name: SecurityWeakness_RDPAuthenticationLevel
data.value:
When presented with an unknown certificate, the RDP client should be configured to either present a warning (Warn me) or abort the connection (Don't connect).
In Options â†’ Types â†’ Remote Desktop, set Authentication level to "Warn me" or "Don't connect".

data.name: SecurityWeakness_RestrictedVaultCreationRecommendation
data.value:
It is preferable to provide rights to users as needed. When enabling this option, vaults will be created with a more limited set of permissions.
In Administration â†’ System Settings â†’ Security, check "Create vaults with restricted access by default."

data.name: SecurityWeakness_RiskyEventsRecommendation
data.value:
Entry events can perform powerful actions such as running an external program or script when an entry is opened. These events represent a risk if they are modified by a malicious actor. These event types can be disabled if they are not needed, or RDM can be configured to show a warning when such an event is about to be executed.
In Administration â†’ System Settings â†’ Security, set Session events to "Warn on risky events", "Disable risky events" or â€œDisable all eventsâ€.

data.name: SecurityWeakness_UsingASecurityProviderIsRecommended
data.value:
By default, passwords are not protected at rest. When a security provider is configured, sensitive data contained in a data source is encrypted.
Security providers are configured in Administration â†’ Security Providers.
